	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, May 27th 7:46 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Tradeable upgrades after froggy crown are shissar scale head band and circlet of vallon.<br><br>As for the serp bracers - well....&nbsp;&nbsp;I have yet to take more than a couple blue after dinging to gain 5 points of weapon skill.  My defensive skills exhibited the same result, too.  The agi to ac formula varies at different agi scores.  Most monk gear has agi on it, so getting agi over 100 is a piece of cake.  With my agility in the 110 range I was getting more like 1 AC per 5 or 6 agi.<br><br>The benefit in skilling up from that extra agi and dex isn't all that great.  You might get your skill ups a hair faster, but you will get far more benefit from just getting a shammy to agi and dex buff you, and from using fast weapons.<br><br>I am a firm believer that serp bracers are not only junk, but indeed the cruel joke that you refer to.  Stats in EQ simply are not that relevant compared to AC, HP, and resists.<br><br>Be careful of wishful thinking when it comes to comparisons.  18 Agi sounds like a hell of a lot, doesn't it?  In truth, you'll be hard-pressed to find a well-studied monk that will support a Serp bracer over a Vox bracer.  Back in the early days of EQ, black pearl jewelry was the rage, because it gave agility.  After lots of testing by lots of hard-core players, there is zero market for black pearl jewelry.  Why?  Because all the testing told the monk community that AC and HP &gt;&gt; Agi and Dex.<br><br>If you want to carry around serps to help skillups after you ding, by all means, do. However, 1.6 dead weight is best used elsewhere.  Unless you're twinked and you have a tink bag, you have to watch every tenth.  And if you're twinked and have a tink bag, you're gonna be wearing better than Vox, most likely.<br><br>I wore Vox till my low 50s, actually.<br><br>I understand the lure and attractiveness of giant stat numbers, and I was one who at first believed that big stats HAVE to be good for something.  The reality is different, though, and wishing something is true doesn't necessarily make it so.<br>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke<br>Member of Tenacity - Druzzil Ro<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a></td></tr>
